The article discusses the Obama Administration's auto restructuring initiative, specifically focusing on the Chrysler-Fiat alliance. The alliance aims to make Chrysler a viable and competitive company in the 21st century. The article highlights the sacrifices made by key stakeholders, including the United Auto Workers (UAW) and Chrysler's largest secured creditors, as well as the contributions of Fiat and Daimler. The details of the alliance include Fiat's intellectual property contribution, the establishment of an independent trust for retiree healthcare benefits, and the involvement of the US Treasury and the governments of Canada and Ontario in providing financial support. The article also mentions the continuation of warranties, dealer financing through GMAC, and the treatment of employees, suppliers, dealers, and creditors during the restructuring process.